Dear PharmEasy Team,

I am writing to express my extreme dissatisfaction with the recurring practice of placing stickers on medicines (tablets) in a manner that compromises their integrity. The stickers are consistently placed on the side of the packaging where the medicine needs to be torn open, causing damage to the tablets and making them unsafe or difficult to use.

I had previously raised this concern in September 2025, requesting that this practice be stopped. Unfortunately, I have received no response, and it appears that my feedback, along with those of other customers, is being ignored. This lack of action is extremely disappointing and raises serious concerns about your commitment to customer safety and satisfaction.

I urge you to address this matter immediately by ensuring that stickers are placed in a way that does not damage the medicine. Continued negligence in this matter may compel me to escalate this complaint to consumer safety authorities.

I expect a prompt acknowledgment of this email and a clear plan of action on how PharmEasy intends to prevent this unsafe practice in the future.

NB: kindly do not make any calls. 

Sincerely,

Sarath 

Order ID: 659165116245897216









On Friday, September 19, 2025, 3:06 PM, Sarath S Nair <sarathsnair67@yahoo.com> wrote:




Dear PharmEasy Team,




I am writing to share feedback regarding the packaging of medicines delivered through your platform. I have noticed that stickers are often placed on the edges of tablet strips, exactly at the spot where people typically peel to take out a tablet. This makes it difficult to access the medicine easily.




For elderly people in particular, it becomes a hectic and uncomfortable task to remove the tablets when stickers obstruct the opening side. A simple adjustment, such as placing the stickers on the reverse side of the strip (where no tablets are accessed), would make the process much more convenient for customers.




I kindly request you to consider this change in your packaging process. It will certainly improve user experience, especially for senior citizens who regularly depend on timely medication.




Thank you for your attention to this matter, and I look forward to your support.




Warm regards,

Sarath

helpdesk_ticket.description_html:
Dear PharmEasy Team,
I am writing to express my extreme dissatisfaction with the recurring practice of placing stickers on medicines (tablets) in a manner that compromises their integrity. The stickers are consistently placed on the side of the packaging where the medicine needs to be torn open, causing damage to the tablets and making them unsafe or difficult to use.
I had previously raised this concern in September 2025, requesting that this practice be stopped. Unfortunately, I have received no response, and it appears that my feedback, along with those of other customers, is being ignored. This lack of action is extremely disappointing and raises serious concerns about your commitment to customer safety and satisfaction.
I urge you to address this matter immediately by ensuring that stickers are placed in a way that does not damage the medicine. Continued negligence in this matter may compel me to escalate this complaint to consumer safety authorities.
I expect a prompt acknowledgment of this email and a clear plan of action on how PharmEasy intends to prevent this unsafe practice in the future.
NB: kindly do not make any calls. 
Sincerely,
Sarath
